tinal tract epithelium","Dermis","Blood vessels","Skeletal elements"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe definitive endoderm gives rise to the \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal tract epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E and its associated organs including the liver, pancreas, and thyroid gland. The other options are derived from different germ layers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural associated structures\u003C/strong\u003E are derived from ectoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermis\u003C/strong\u003E is derived from mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E are derived from mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkeletal elements\u003C/strong\u003E are derived from mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding germ layer derivatives is crucial for comprehending both normal development and congenital abnormalities. The endoderm specifically forms the epithelial lining of the respiratory and digestive tracts, as well as the parenchyma of associated organs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The definitive endoderm gives rise to the gastrointestinal tract epithelium and associated organs including liver, pancreas, and thyroid.","The three primary germ layers (endoderm, mesoderm, ectoderm) each form distinct tissue types during embryological development."],"references":["Wong JC, Gao SY, Lees JG, Best MB, Wang R, Tuch BE. Definitive endoderm derived from human embryonic stem cells highly express the integrin receptors alphaV and beta5. Cell Adh Migr. 2010 Jan-Mar;4(1):39-45. doi: 10.4161/cam.4.1.10627. Epub 2010 Jan 13. PMID: 20026907; PMCID: PMC2852556.","Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48883"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15986"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48883"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T22:43:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T22:44:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8677"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63430"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":